48:28.000 --> 48:31.000
of course, at their own expense and in their working hours.

48:31.000 --> 48:35.000
And the company can explain that in order to train you,

48:35.000 --> 48:39.000
to plan training and development of training,

48:39.000 --> 48:46.000
we need to understand your expectations, your ambitions, and plan for each career.

48:47.000 --> 48:52.000
This is a universal wording that shows that in this project,

48:52.000 --> 48:57.000
the interests of the company, the interests of the employees are the same.

48:57.000 --> 49:01.000
And already the third point is when we start planning the project.

49:01.000 --> 49:07.000
Not earlier, as any action from the management of the staff, as we know,

49:07.000 --> 49:11.000
immediately strains the employees if they do not understand what we are talking about.

49:11.000 --> 49:17.000
And since career planning affects either certain departments or the company as a whole,

49:17.000 --> 49:21.000
it is important to give people the necessary information as soon as possible,

49:21.000 --> 49:25.000
and in the simplest and most understandable form.

49:25.000 --> 49:29.000
The next point is the creation of a career path map.

49:29.000 --> 49:33.000
Further, the methodology of assessing the staff with clear indicators,

49:33.000 --> 49:37.000
what we talked about a little earlier, the assessment of the staff,

49:37.000 --> 49:39.000
the discussion of the results.

49:39.000 --> 49:43.000
And here is a very important point that, of course, we try to make career planning

49:43.000 --> 49:49.000
as objective as possible, and the methods of assessment, as the management requires from us,

49:49.000 --> 49:52.000
to be as objective and formalized as possible.

49:52.000 --> 49:56.000
But in reality, each company has a policy,

49:56.000 --> 50:04.000
and, as a rule, the results of the assessment become the subject of a discussion of the higher management

50:04.000 --> 50:11.000
about certain employees who are the most interesting and important to the company.

50:11.000 --> 50:15.000
Therefore, before performing any actions,

50:15.000 --> 50:23.000
usually the results of the evaluation of employees become the subject of a discussion of the higher management.

50:23.000 --> 50:29.000
And only after that we move on to the stage of feedback to the employee on the results of the assessment,

50:29.000 --> 50:37.000
career planning, what we discussed a little earlier, the very methodology of conducting an interview,

50:37.000 --> 50:40.000
and the norming of the labor payment matrix.

50:40.000 --> 50:45.000
Here it is very important to norm labor payment relative to grades,

50:45.000 --> 50:49.000
and grades that are universal throughout the company,

50:49.000 --> 50:56.000
but the labor payment matrix can vary from regions and from countries where certain units are located.

50:56.000 --> 50:58.000
But here is a very important point,

50:58.000 --> 51:06.000
that each employee will be able to compare himself with other employees based on the grade,

51:06.000 --> 51:10.000
and not on the basis of the salary, which depends on regions and on countries.

51:10.000 --> 51:19.000
And now we will discuss the mistakes that usually occur in companies in the area of career management.

51:20.000 --> 51:26.000
The first mistake is the lack of career management function.

51:26.000 --> 51:33.000
And on this slide we can see what problems the nature of the process leads to.

51:33.000 --> 51:41.000
The nature of the process leads to the fact that we underestimate the ambitions and potential of the candidates we hire.

51:41.000 --> 51:47.000
As a result, the candidates either do not apply, the current trial period increases,

51:47.000 --> 51:50.000
the current staff during the first year of work,

51:50.000 --> 51:55.000
the dissatisfaction of the employees with their position in the company,

51:55.000 --> 51:58.000
and the resultativeness of their work decreases.

51:58.000 --> 52:02.000
The next point is extravagant HR decisions.

52:02.000 --> 52:10.000
As we know, the management sometimes likes to change the positioning of a particular employee unexpectedly,

52:10.000 --> 52:12.000
including top managers.

52:12.000 --> 52:18.000
They want to shift the position to a new one without discussing it with the employees.

52:18.000 --> 52:22.000
Some managers, reasonably or not,

52:22.000 --> 52:32.000
believe that any promotion that is accompanied by an increase in the salary should be desirable by the employees.

52:32.000 --> 52:34.000
There is such a mechanistic approach,

52:34.000 --> 52:42.000
especially for the company owners, who believe that any HR decision is possible for money.

52:42.000 --> 52:46.000
We understand that in the reality of business, this is not always the case.

52:46.000 --> 52:56.000
In order to prevent mistakes of our management, it is very important to plan a career for the long-term and the most accurate.

52:56.000 --> 53:01.000
The third point is the financial losses of the company.

53:01.000 --> 53:08.000
If we talk about training, then some companies train everyone for everything or something,

53:08.000 --> 53:17.000
and as a result, if the training process and training plan are not connected with the planning of the career and with the strategic goals of the company,

53:17.000 --> 53:22.000
then it is mostly wasted money.

53:22.000 --> 53:25.000
That is, it is not an optimal investment in training and development.

53:26.000 --> 53:34.000
Further, the consequences of the mistake of the absence of the function of managing the career are the uncontrollable struggle of the employees' ambitions,

53:34.000 --> 53:47.000
who try to prove to the management who is cooler, who is more worthy of promotion and increase in salary.

53:47.000 --> 53:52.000
As you understand, this does not increase the ability of the department to work.

53:52.000 --> 53:56.000
This affects the atmosphere in the team negatively.

53:56.000 --> 54:01.000
In order to keep the employees, we have to do it with a salary.

54:01.000 --> 54:10.000
As a result, the company's costs for the salary increase, which is also not optimal.

54:10.000 --> 54:17.000
In the next slide, we see the next problem, which is also related to the planning of the career.

54:17.000 --> 54:19.000
This is a lack of systematic.

54:19.000 --> 54:25.000
For example, in large companies, the planning of the career is done in one department,

54:25.000 --> 54:30.000
training is done in another department, and the evaluation and adaptation is done in the next departments.

54:30.000 --> 54:36.000
Accordingly, these processes have an internal logic, but are not connected with each other.

54:36.000 --> 54:43.000
As a result, the management system itself loses its effectiveness.

54:43.000 --> 54:54.000
Here I tried to show how the planning of the career, which directly affects the personnel decisions,

54:54.000 --> 55:03.000
how all the functions of the staff management can be systematized and act in the system.

55:03.000 --> 55:11.000
The next mistake is the lack of management of ambitions.

55:11.000 --> 55:17.000
There are two possible situations.

55:17.000 --> 55:23.000
On the one hand, when an employee whose ambition the company did not notice in time,

55:23.000 --> 55:30.000
he somehow gets an offer from another company, usually competitors in the same industry,

55:30.000 --> 55:32.000
and leaves us.

55:33.000 --> 55:42.000
That is, he will now do his job in favor of our competitors, which is absolutely unprofitable for us.

55:42.000 --> 55:49.000
Or the employee, on the contrary, has low ambitions, and according to the logic of the company's development,

55:49.000 --> 55:55.000
we start promoting it, because it initially seems to us, thanks to the stereotype,

55:55.000 --> 55:59.000
that each employee is interested in promotion and salary increase.

55:59.000 --> 56:01.000
In practice, this is not the case.

56:01.000 --> 56:09.000
Some employees are ready to take their position, they have reached the balance of life and work to which they aspired,

56:09.000 --> 56:16.000
and therefore they do not dream of any promotion, and in addition, they will create obstacles.

56:16.000 --> 56:20.000
But depending on whether they can honestly say about it or not.

56:20.000 --> 56:24.000
How is this problem solved?

56:24.000 --> 56:31.000
This is the detailing of the career ladder with a clear system of requirements for all competences,

56:31.000 --> 56:37.000
both professional and managerial, and with a clear attachment to the level of wage.

56:37.000 --> 56:47.000
Here is a pyramid, on which we see about 11 career levels in the company.

56:47.000 --> 56:51.000
This is an example of a consulting company.

56:51.000 --> 56:58.000
In consulting, almost all employees are the same, and do the same.

56:58.000 --> 57:03.000
But in order to keep the competence of the employee within the company,

57:03.000 --> 57:09.000
and in order not to overpay the beginners and retain more experienced employees,

57:09.000 --> 57:15.000
a very detailed career matrix is built.

57:15.000 --> 57:24.000
Here, as an example, I have given, and we see that in the company this matrix of 11 or 20 levels

57:24.000 --> 57:28.000
can be assigned to the entire professional life of an employee,

57:28.000 --> 57:32.000
and ideally, to keep him for the rest of his life in one company.

57:32.000 --> 57:37.000
This often happens in large global Western companies, as we know.

57:37.000 --> 57:41.000
And here, too, two situations are possible.

57:41.000 --> 57:46.000
A number of employees are not ready to wait until two years later, three years later,

57:46.000 --> 57:49.000
and will be considered for the next career step,

57:49.000 --> 57:54.000
and they simply go to other companies, and immediately take higher positions.

57:54.000 --> 57:58.000
But for another number of employees, on the contrary,

57:58.000 --> 58:05.000
they are close to such a career planning option as life in one company,

58:05.000 --> 58:08.000
and work in one company, in one industry all their life,

58:08.000 --> 58:16.000
and then such a high career ladder is just adequate for their motivation,

58:16.000 --> 58:21.000
for their promotion, for their life inside the company.

58:21.000 --> 58:27.000
We have already noted a point that is related to the fact that not always the ambitions of an employee

58:27.000 --> 58:31.000
and the opportunities of a company for its promotion coincide.

58:32.000 --> 58:38.000
And, of course, most often, a special analytical work is necessary

58:38.000 --> 58:42.000
in order to understand how within the framework of this organizational structure

58:42.000 --> 58:45.000
our employees have the opportunities for career growth.

58:45.000 --> 58:51.000
And on this slide, I tried to reflect how we can solve this problem

58:51.000 --> 58:55.000
as a violation of the business needs and ambitions of the employee.

58:55.000 --> 58:59.000
For example, we take all the adjacent departments

58:59.000 --> 59:04.000
with the employee we are considering.

59:04.000 --> 59:07.000
In this example, this is the marketing department.

59:07.000 --> 59:11.000
Let's imagine that our employee, who is dissatisfied with his position,

59:11.000 --> 59:17.000
is at the level of a specialist, and we, based on the results of his assessment,

59:17.000 --> 59:20.000
have estimated that, yes, indeed, his knowledge and experience

59:20.000 --> 59:23.000
are superior to the requirements of this position.

59:23.000 --> 59:29.000
But in the marketing department we do not see such opportunities for promotion,

59:29.000 --> 59:34.000
as all the positions are occupied, as we see, by the head of the group and the head of the department.

59:34.000 --> 59:39.000
Then we begin to analyze all adjacent professional areas.

59:39.000 --> 59:45.000
In relation to marketing, this is CRM, working with clients, this is sales,

59:45.000 --> 59:47.000
and there can also be projects.

59:47.000 --> 59:53.000
And in these verticals we can see possible vacancies.

59:53.000 --> 59:58.000
Thus, for this specialist, we can show that he has the opportunity

59:58.000 --> 01:00:02.000
to rotate horizontally to other adjacent departments,

01:00:02.000 --> 01:00:06.000
in which he will gain new experience and new knowledge,

01:00:06.000 --> 01:00:11.000
which will later help him make significant progress in his career,

01:00:12.000 --> 01:00:18.000
depending on how much we evaluate his managerial potential and skills,

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:23.000
and how much he really wants to move in the management vertical.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:28.000
For a certain amount of time, such horizontal rotations

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:32.000
for the employees in adjacent departments can look very profitable.

01:00:32.000 --> 01:00:39.000
In this regard, the fact that the employee himself expands the area of his professional competencies,

01:00:39.000 --> 01:00:42.000
and he perfectly understands that at the highest level,

01:00:42.000 --> 01:00:49.000
at which these functions are combined, for example, at the position of sales director,

01:00:49.000 --> 01:00:55.000
or PR and advertising director, all the knowledge that he receives at this first stage,

01:00:55.000 --> 01:01:00.000
passing the rotation in adjacent departments, these knowledge will be very important to him.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:04.000
And if the employee really looks into the distant future,

01:01:04.000 --> 01:01:12.000
he will take our arguments with optimism and the opportunity to rotate to adjacent departments.

01:01:12.000 --> 01:01:18.000
But on this example, I have given a very small slide in English,

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
but this is not important at all.

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:23.000
The most important thing in this slide is logic.

01:01:23.000 --> 01:01:27.000
The logic of career planning options.

01:01:27.000 --> 01:01:36.000
When we show the requirements for the increasing grades in the first line,

01:01:36.000 --> 01:01:41.000
here TA stands for trainee analyst,

01:01:41.000 --> 01:01:47.000
the next level A1 is the analyst of the first level, the analyst of the second, third,

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:51.000
and then the leading analysts of the first, second, third, and fourth grades.

01:01:51.000 --> 01:01:57.000
This is an example of career planning for programmers.

01:01:57.000 --> 01:02:03.000
And in the first line, the main requirements for these grades are indicated, which are common.

01:02:03.000 --> 01:02:06.000
One or another logic of career development.

01:02:06.000 --> 01:02:13.000
The second line shows the professional logic of career development,

01:02:13.000 --> 01:02:16.000
and the third line shows the management logic.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:24.000
As we can see, here we give programmers the opportunity to grow in professional level,

01:02:24.000 --> 01:02:30.000
and also to start their management growth from the level of grade 3.

01:02:30.000 --> 01:02:34.000
A person can already take on more and more management functions,

01:02:34.000 --> 01:02:37.000
and we show it to him in a special third line.

01:02:37.000 --> 01:02:44.000
I can say that based on experience, when we discuss this topic with an employee

01:02:44.000 --> 01:02:52.000
and give a well-designed map of career paths,

01:02:52.000 --> 01:02:55.000
it makes a very positive impression on the employees,

01:02:55.000 --> 01:03:01.000
because they finally show their capabilities in this company in a clear form,

01:03:01.000 --> 01:03:06.000
and the requirements are clearly shown, depending on the grade.

01:03:06.000 --> 01:03:12.000
As you know, there are such curiosities when we hire a little inexperienced employee.

01:03:12.000 --> 01:03:16.000
The first three months, six months, we teach him energetically,

01:03:16.000 --> 01:03:19.000
and it seems to him that he already knows everything in his field.

01:03:19.000 --> 01:03:29.000
And here, a very cooling factor is that we show this employee,

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:34.000
who already believes that he knows everything, and he is worthy of being transferred to a higher grade,

01:03:34.000 --> 01:03:40.000
we show him such a matrix of career paths and requirements for each grade.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:45.000
And when we tell a person that he has studied these three technologies perfectly,

01:03:45.000 --> 01:03:50.000
which are necessary for this grade, but there are 15 technologies in the requirements of this grade,

01:03:50.000 --> 01:03:56.000
the company will give him the opportunity to rotate in projects or in units,

01:03:56.000 --> 01:04:03.000
during which he will have the opportunity to develop all his 10 other skills,

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:12.000
and thus, after some evaluation, we will be able to consider you for promotion to the next grade.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:17.000
Thus, the information of employees plays a key role here,

01:04:17.000 --> 01:04:23.000
because if an employee does not have information, he may have inadequate ambitions.

01:04:23.000 --> 01:04:28.000
When we give information to a person, we show him the general rules of the game,

01:04:28.000 --> 01:04:33.000
we show him that these general rules are adopted by the higher management of the company,

01:04:33.000 --> 01:04:36.000
and they work for each employee, not only for him.

01:04:36.000 --> 01:04:41.000
And the whole logic of the development of colleagues is subordinate to these rules,

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:49.000
and this makes absolute clarity in this corporate game, in this corporate life.

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:56.000
And employees feel more confident on the one hand, and on the other hand, feel more protected.

01:04:56.000 --> 01:05:04.000
The employee understands that only his efforts and his energy and initiative depend on his career progress.

01:05:04.000 --> 01:05:11.000
And with the help of such a map, it is very effective to motivate employees to those projects,

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:17.000
on which they would not have agreed with other information.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:26.000
For example, in this matrix, we have made such an important point as the need for each employee

01:05:26.000 --> 01:05:32.000
to work in customer support before a certain grade.

01:05:32.000 --> 01:05:42.000
And here we put it as a mandatory condition and justify to programmers that only by working in this function,

01:05:42.000 --> 01:05:47.000
in the function of customer support, they will acquire very important skills.

01:05:47.000 --> 01:05:50.000
First, they will better understand the needs of customers,

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:55.000
they will better understand what mistakes customers most often face,

01:05:55.000 --> 01:05:58.000
they will better understand the code that they did not write,

01:05:58.000 --> 01:06:02.000
they will better learn how to work with this code optimally,

01:06:02.000 --> 01:06:05.000
and find mistakes in it and correct them.

01:06:05.000 --> 01:06:10.000
And this will play a role in the next attestation.

01:06:10.000 --> 01:06:16.000
Thus, in such a detailed map of career paths,

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:19.000
it is possible to achieve a combination of interests,

01:06:19.000 --> 01:06:23.000
on the one hand, the logic of the development of the employees themselves,

01:06:23.000 --> 01:06:28.000
the logic of the development of their ambitions, and the logic of the business needs.

01:06:28.000 --> 01:06:37.000
Here, of course, business needs play a key role in this career path matrix.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:40.000
When it fits on one page, this is also a crucial point.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:46.000
When each employee can see the horizon of his development right on one page,

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:53.000
this is very important for him, such an important, obvious, normal logic.

01:06:53.000 --> 01:06:58.000
And this document becomes open, and each employee understands what is required of him,

01:06:58.000 --> 01:07:02.000
and what efforts he can make in order to advance in his career,

01:07:02.000 --> 01:07:06.000
and to have more arguments for the next interview,

01:07:06.000 --> 01:07:10.000
based on the results of his previous activity.

01:07:10.000 --> 01:07:18.000
In the next slide, we see that it is dedicated to the shortcomings of the personnel decision-making system.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:22.000
For example, no matter how well we plan the career of employees,

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:26.000
if we do not have a decision-making tool and promotion of employees,

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:30.000
such planning is rather provocative,

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:39.000
because we include ambitions, we give hope to employees, but we cannot support them.

01:07:39.000 --> 01:07:46.000
Thus, in order to connect the planning of the career with the adoption of management decisions,

01:07:46.000 --> 01:07:49.000
a unified information system works very well for this purpose.

01:07:49.000 --> 01:07:56.000
When all our employees and the organizational structure live in one software system,

01:07:56.000 --> 01:08:02.000
and the management, when it has a need to consider or compare several employees,

01:08:02.000 --> 01:08:05.000
can identify the best candidate for promotion,

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:10.000
the management can do it with just a few clicks of a mouse,

01:08:10.000 --> 01:08:13.000
get a comparative report on several employees,

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:17.000
and can make a management decision.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:20.000
In addition, this decision will be argued,

01:08:20.000 --> 01:08:24.000
because it will be based on objective factors.

01:08:24.000 --> 01:08:28.000
Accordingly, this is the engine of the process of planning the career.

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:37.000
In the next slide, I would like to reflect that different little things can play a very important role in planning the career.

01:08:37.000 --> 01:08:41.000
For example, during one assessment center,

01:08:41.000 --> 01:08:44.000
when we identified management competencies,

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:52.000
various assessment tools were used, including tests and interview on competencies,

01:08:52.000 --> 01:09:03.000
we aimed to select the stars that we could recommend to management promotion based on objective factors.

01:09:03.000 --> 01:09:07.000
The only thing is that in this company, which was global,

01:09:07.000 --> 01:09:16.000
promotion was associated with the need to change the place of residence, move to another region.

01:09:16.000 --> 01:09:28.000
Yes, a person won a salary, and the company considered that this is a great happiness.

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:32.000
If you are nominated for the stars,

01:09:32.000 --> 01:09:39.000
you have such wonderful opportunities as moving to other regions with a salary increase and a position.

01:09:40.000 --> 01:09:46.000
During my interview, I was surprised to see a very strong candidate,

01:09:46.000 --> 01:09:56.000
who showed very strong results in various tests and objectively entered the category of stars.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:01.000
When I saw a very complaining expression on his face,

01:10:01.000 --> 01:10:07.000
our interview ended with him asking not to include him in the reservists,

01:10:07.000 --> 01:10:11.000
because he just doesn't want to change his place of residence.

01:10:11.000 --> 01:10:15.000
Here he has relatives, here he has a big family, here his children study.

01:10:15.000 --> 01:10:23.000
He looked with such sadness and said that despite the fact that we spent so much time on him,

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:31.000
and indeed he is very strong in results, in his management potential, in his ability to learn,

01:10:31.000 --> 01:10:41.000
nevertheless, there was a banal household obstacle, that he just didn't want to change his place of work.

01:10:41.000 --> 01:10:47.000
Therefore, he was not ready to move forward within the global framework.

01:10:47.000 --> 01:10:52.000
Within the framework of this region, there was no opportunity for promotion,

01:10:52.000 --> 01:10:56.000
but this did not create any discomfort for him.

01:10:56.000 --> 01:11:03.000
Thus, during this deep assessment, the company finally received information

01:11:03.000 --> 01:11:07.000
that the person simply does not want to move forward for household reasons,

01:11:07.000 --> 01:11:11.000
for family reasons, otherwise it would not have known about it.

01:11:13.000 --> 01:11:19.000
Also, in the next slide, I am talking about neglecting the context.

01:11:19.000 --> 01:11:25.000
The fact is that when we form a pool of reservists,

01:11:25.000 --> 01:11:30.000
we select stars using numerous assessment procedures,

01:11:30.000 --> 01:11:35.000
and we attract a lot of attention to employees,

01:11:35.000 --> 01:11:39.000
we develop them, create individual development plans for them.

01:11:39.000 --> 01:11:44.000
This, of course, objectively causes some anxiety for the managers.

01:11:45.000 --> 01:11:49.000
The manager understands, either for objective or subjective reasons,

01:11:49.000 --> 01:11:52.000
that he will not be able to move forward in his career,

01:11:52.000 --> 01:11:55.000
or he is busy in a higher position,

01:11:55.000 --> 01:12:01.000
and he naturally has anxiety about his high-potential employees.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:05.000
There are even cases when the management of the company's staff and management

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:09.000
does not control enough what is happening in the department,

01:12:09.000 --> 01:12:16.000
such high-potential employees easily receive offers from competitors,

01:12:16.000 --> 01:12:22.000
and for them the direct manager creates a situation

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:26.000
when a person simply accepts another offer and leaves for another company.

01:12:26.000 --> 01:12:29.000
Accordingly, this company has lost money,

01:12:29.000 --> 01:12:33.000
invested time in this employee, and it is already losing it.

01:12:33.000 --> 01:12:37.000
How to overcome this obstacle?

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:41.000
Since the company is large, it has many departments, many enterprises,

01:12:41.000 --> 01:12:44.000
if not even enough enterprises,

01:12:44.000 --> 01:12:47.000
but we can say that the company is growing,

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:50.000
and therefore vacancies arise in different departments.

01:12:50.000 --> 01:12:54.000
If the company postulates that the employee is preparing,

01:12:54.000 --> 01:12:59.000
and the company prepares him for the position of his direct manager,

01:12:59.000 --> 01:13:05.000
and that a person can be prepared for a higher position in another department

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:08.000
or in another enterprise in another region,

01:13:08.000 --> 01:13:13.000
this usually relaxes the situation and removes the conflict of interests

01:13:13.000 --> 01:13:17.000
of the direct boss and his high-potential employee.

01:13:17.000 --> 01:13:23.000
Here, of course, the issue can be solved with the help of internal PR

01:13:23.000 --> 01:13:26.000
and with the help of correct management decisions.

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:31.000
When there are real personnel shifts from one department to another,

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:37.000
between enterprises, only then the direct bosses will not feel the threat

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:41.000
from their high-potential subordinates.

01:13:41.000 --> 01:13:46.000
In the next slide, I describe another obstacle to the planning of a career

01:13:46.000 --> 01:13:48.000
as a local interest.

01:13:48.000 --> 01:13:56.000
The fact is that the direct manager is least interested in the career of his subordinates.

01:13:56.000 --> 01:14:02.000
Why? Because he simply does not want to lose a strong employee.

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:06.000
And, of course, here we immediately get this obstacle,

01:14:06.000 --> 01:14:13.000
that the directors themselves are far from always ready to give the management of the staff their stars

01:14:13.000 --> 01:14:15.000
and point to them.

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:20.000
On the contrary, they want to hide it and want to keep their employee in their department as long as possible.

01:14:20.000 --> 01:14:23.000
But this is very unprofitable for the company,

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:27.000
and this company is very likely to lose an ambitious employee.

01:14:27.000 --> 01:14:29.000
And if the employee is not ambitious enough,

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:33.000
then the company may lose the opportunity to develop this employee,

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:36.000
expand its functionality and responsibility.

01:14:36.000 --> 01:14:41.000
This problem is solved by the fact that the project on managing personnel,

01:14:41.000 --> 01:14:43.000
on managing the career of a staff member,

01:14:43.000 --> 01:14:50.000
it has a single center, becomes systematic and is managed independently.

01:14:50.000 --> 01:14:55.000
This is usually done by the management of the staff of HR or by an external provider.

01:14:55.000 --> 01:15:00.000
This business process is managed independently,

01:15:00.000 --> 01:15:03.000
all data is processed centrally,

01:15:03.000 --> 01:15:08.000
and it is very important that this process has a total and unyielding character,

01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:12.000
so that each manager understands that this is not only about his department,

01:15:12.000 --> 01:15:15.000
this process concerns the company as a whole.

01:15:15.000 --> 01:15:23.000
Then the obstacles from the direct managers will not be able to be realized,

01:15:23.000 --> 01:15:25.000
despite the fact that they can be,

01:15:25.000 --> 01:15:28.000
but nevertheless it will be more difficult to implement.

01:15:29.000 --> 01:15:34.000
The next possible problem in planning a career is a narrow understanding of the process itself.

01:15:34.000 --> 01:15:39.000
If the company understands this only as promotion vertically,

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:44.000
then there are two possible problems, as we have already said.

01:15:44.000 --> 01:15:49.000
The first is promotion of a highly professional specialist without management competencies,

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:56.000
or an obstacle from the boss in working with this employee,

01:15:56.000 --> 01:15:59.000
only because he feels that he has management ambitions.

01:15:59.000 --> 01:16:04.000
Accordingly, the solution to this problem is postulating in the company

01:16:04.000 --> 01:16:07.000
and advertising, internal PR in the company,

01:16:07.000 --> 01:16:11.000
horizontal career, cross-departmental,

01:16:11.000 --> 01:16:16.000
and vertical careers, but in cross-departmental.

01:16:16.000 --> 01:16:19.000
This helps to relieve unnecessary tension.

01:16:19.000 --> 01:16:24.000
Artificial intelligence, but this is the next slide,

01:16:24.000 --> 01:16:29.000
shows us the problem that concerns a number of international ambitious companies,

01:16:29.000 --> 01:16:34.000
which, using different methods of corporate culture,

01:16:35.000 --> 01:16:39.000
specifically provoke competition among employees,

01:16:39.000 --> 01:16:42.000
specifically provoke their ambitions,

01:16:42.000 --> 01:16:45.000
and create a trend for career promotion,

01:16:45.000 --> 01:16:49.000
and anti-trend for long-term position.

01:16:49.000 --> 01:16:55.000
